segments.text: the College of Education, who has been at Texas A&M since 1970, shortly after the college was formed.

And Dean Cole is going to share with me, I hope, some ideas, some insights, some perceptions of all of the things that have happened and all of the changes, or at least some of them, but basically changes.
And that's one of the things I'm focusing on and on the different administrations.
I have a lot of questions now after 653 organizational behavior course about the structure of the organization.
I realize that I'm just somebody peeking in the windows, and I don't have the whole picture because I'm not intimately involved except in the different roles that I've been involved.
So there are some questions, and I'll deal with those maybe later and ask you about leadership styles or conflict management
even just the management in general.
But I know you're very intimately aware.
But anyway, basically, you've seen the questions and you know what I'm doing and why I'm doing it and the fact that I'm really looking for something other than a true history.
I'm really wanting to find how people are feeling and what kinds of things.
And you have been in a unique situation because you worked so closely with Dean Hubert
and you have worked equally as hard as Dean Corrigan, and you're there, and you're heavy into the decision-making.
So shall we talk about changes first, Major?
Write a book, do you realize that?
Why don't you?
In your spare time?
I've just spent the last three weeks trying to put one little bitty paper together that I'm presenting next week.
It's been an incredible amount of time.
What's it on?
its own improved decision-making, as a matter of fact.
Good.
Will you share anything?
Sure.
It really is an outgrowth out of the... Actually, what it is is 639, all in one paper.
Wonderful.
It's a great course.
It's still one of the best.
It's what I have finally gotten to do, exactly what I asked you guys to do.
That's great.
I sure hope you'll get through.
Well, all right.
We started when the college opened in 1969.
It had evolved, you know, from the Department of Education.
But women was, everybody's talking about the big change, the impact of women in the college, okay?
The focus and the mission of the college has been and will be and always had the teaching, the research, and the
and the service, maybe let's start with that.
With how has that, or has that changed in focus, or has the focus of those, of that mission changed in any way between the Pubert era and the Corrigan era, for example?
The big difference between the early years, early 70s, and where we are today, is that we had
a very young faculty.
Just beginning, we had a few folks who were fairly well established.
But we had really come in primarily as teachers, graduate level as well as graduate level.
And we were very immature.
And I don't mean that in a negative sense.
I mean in terms of development.
We were very immature during that time.

And as we went through the early 70s, about 73, 74, when the big growth spokes began to hit, through the late 70s, about a five-year span of 73 to 78, we were increasing in the college anywhere from 11% to 14% a year for five years steadily.
We were the fastest growing college of education in the country as far as we know.
during that period of time.
We were going against national trends.
As a general rule, enrollment teacher education was going down.
Graduate enrollment was a slow growth pattern.
Undergraduate was phenomenal.
There was one year in the era that finances were good, growth and everything else, that we added 10 new positions in the college in one year.
And that's 10 tenure track positions.
Now, that hasn't happened before or since.
But there were a number of years now where we had four to six new positions.
So during that mid-'70s period, it grew very rapidly.
And I think it's really a tribute to Dr. Hubert and to Dr. Corbin, both.
That first Dr. Hubert, from the standpoint of moving that quickly, plus with the institution itself, is changing very dramatically at that time.
that we were able to maintain and, in fact, have a cohesive goal toward which we were all trying to move.
We've gone from that immaturity of people really focusing on what I would perceive as a more common goal to whereas now, where we have a common goal, we also have a large number of faculty that
that in a major college like we have here, you have to have both kinds of folks.
But at the same time, each has to recognize the worth and the value of both kinds.
An undergraduate program with 2,500 students and that your bread and butter is teacher education and put all your apples in the research basket.
Similarly, you can't have a graduate program with a thousand kids and put all your apples
You've got to have a balanced program and that's sometimes very difficult to maintain.
There are a lot of forces working both from that university and from within the university
more toward the graduate area of exclusion.
Well, not exclusion, but the graduate program first priority or maybe even second priority.

And I don't know that we need to say one is first and one is second, but rather recognize that they're both very important missions of the college and recognize that both these resources are actually complementary to each other rather than exclusionary to each other.
And I think that's a tension that we have today
much greater than we had 10, 15 years ago.
Does it vary from department to department?
Yeah, it would have to, because we have one, two, three departments that are almost exclusively graduate.
Of course, their emphasis is going to be graduate.
So we're really talking in terms of those departments which have both undergraduate and graduate programs.
OK, which only is about three.
Well, it's actually for when you consider Ed Psych.
They don't have undergraduate majors, but they do have a tremendous undergraduate service responsibility in terms of the introductory Ed Psych course plus the special ed program.

service come in because I am hearing that a lot of departments are saying we are the research department and such and so and so is the service and they don't do the research that we do and that kind of thing.
Where does service fit in?
Service sort of tags along and gets plugged in realistically and is not a part of the somewhat advisedly.
It is and it isn't.
You have a responsibility there
But you can't make it in service on its own.
We like to look at all three of them together and recognize that everybody's going to have different roles proportionately in each of the three areas.
And I think as 15 years ago, everyone pretty well focused on the teaching role and some service role and some research role, that emphasis has now shifted to
the research emphasis at third.

Ideally, those three would come together so that your service would in fact be an extension of your research and your admissions teacher education by doing research and development work with the schools.
We would then also, at the same time, be purposes or responding needs that they might have.
And then from that grows new information and things that could be integrated into teaching.
So ideally, all three of them complement each other.
I guess that's a major way that we changed.
That's not inconsistent with the way higher education in general
typically changes.
You know, you started a teaching institution and the profession of higher education is hierarchically structured such that the epitome of being a full professor is a researcher, publisher,
expert in the field, and so forth.
This is more toward graduate work than undergraduate work.
And then promotion and tenure and all of that is always still, there's still that pressure, and it's still based on your research.
Well, and your teaching, too.
But that's what's more important.
Well, that's what the perception of the faculty is.
Where the dean has played, the coordinator has played a very strong role in this.
is trying to make some kind of a balance in there, recognizing that when you have a faculty of 175, 500 majors, that there are many different roles within the college that have to be played.
And that not everyone needs to, nor should, fit that research program.
A faculty of 175 total?
That's headcount.
That includes health and PE lecturers.
And EDCI has 100?
Oh, no, no, no, no, no.
No.
Well, we were just talking about, he must have been talking about support staff.
He said he had a staff, like, and there was 100 people in his staff.
Well, I applied for my graduate students to graduate assistants as well.
Oh, okay.
EDCI faculty were numbered right about 40.
Oh, okay.
Regular tenure track faculty, about 40.
I see.
I imagine that that's, I can get that, those figures and all that, you know, what the breakdown is by the department.
Okay, good.
All right.
Now, you have always taught, right?
You've always had some teaching assignment limited or?
Since 75.
Okay.
Has the growth that we have experienced in the college affected your ability to work with the students?
the time or the, you know, whatever.
I should know it.
Well, it's interesting you should ask that.
This particular semester, because this semester I'm teaching the foundations of secondary education, and typically I would go to my classes without two sections of 50 each.
And just out of sheer necessity, I had to open both those up to the room.
I had 66 kids, which
I have seen where it's definitely taken a toll on me in terms of my ability to service that need.
You still teach the graduate course every semester?
Yes, in the spring.
Once a semester?
I mean, once a year.
Yeah.
OK.
In terms of the student affairs office, the thing that has enabled us to really be responsive to the kids, the single thing, I have a database and knowledge of people who deal with those things.
There's no way that we could have effectively given them the kids that we do deal with.
Good staff, obviously, but in terms of just sheer numbers, we haven't added a secretarial position in the student affairs area in 12 years.
How many years have you been in this position?
Since 1983.
And I also was acting in it the year that Dean Limbaugh was acting dean, in between the Huber and the Corrigan, during that year I was acting.
And I went back for one year as assistant dean.
What about collaboration?
And being from the eighth floor, looking down, and you can probably tell me more about interaction between departments, more so than
among the departments, because I get that probably from department heads as far as collaborative work within their departments.
But how do you see that collaborative effort?
And I know the inquiry deals that Dean Corgan instigated have been very helpful in that.
What else?
Or how do you perceive it?
Is it more or less?
I think overall it's more.
I'm not sure if you're able to look at it
in 1969 dollars and 1987 dollars and build that inflation factor.
And I'm not sure if it would be more or not.
But because we have more faculty and so forth, it certainly seems like we have more.
And I know there are more specific instances where faculty are working across departments with each other.
And after that, it was limited.
The programs 15, 17 years ago were not that complex either.
It was fairly straightforward teacher education.
We didn't have adult education or vocational education.
We did not have special education.
We just basically had straight elementary and secondary certification.
And then as our knowledge base has increased, too, with respect to teacher education, what it takes to support that.
Then the college has grown and adapted to it and more people are involved in cross-disciplines.
It leads to where we have so many non-traditional kinds of programs as well, such as the Human Performance Lab and how to do physical therapy and pre-nursing and pre-occupational exercise technology.
Okay.
What about perceptions of others of the college?
And certainly you've been here and have had a feel for how this college is perceived by the others in the university and then even in the more external environment.
Yeah, I've seen a lot of change in that.
I think the college has started out in a very strong position within the university and has maintained
that strong position, and when I say strong, in relationship to the other disciplines of the university.
Okay.
Especially for a major, especially since A&M has moved into the, quote, major university research status, has maintained a strong position because of our roots.
And that is, early on, Dr. Hubert was both Dean of Liberal Arts, actually Dean of Arts and Sciences.
Right.
and then Dean of Liberal Arts and Dean of Education.
He, in fact, had hired many of the faculty in Arts and Sciences.
So established before it was even required what's called the University Council on Teacher Education.
And that was an interdisciplinary group
housed in the College of Education, but involved other faculty and other disciplines who had responsibility for the teaching fields and the content of the degree outside.
Is that still in effect?
That's still very much in effect.
Yeah, it's a requirement now by NCAID and TEA that you have this kind of a council.
But it works here, I think, much more effectively than in most institutions because of the historical base.
and that we have so much tradition and so much history of a very close relationship between the disciplines and the College of Ed.

I think because also the number of our faculty, as that has evolved, the kinds of faculty that we've been able to recruit, and going back to your question on the goal about interaction, interdisciplinary kinds of things, the way that our people work with others on campus has
been able to maintain that strong position, both realistically and in perception.
I can say that we have always, from the higher administration, been treated fairly.
By that you mean?
In the allowance of resources and all of that?
Yeah.

I think if you were to displace this college of education in a similar institution like a UT or what have you, that you'd see a major difference in the kinds of resources that we have been given and increasingly the kinds of resources that we've got.
Is that attributed more to the leadership?
Is the dean responsible for, just like the department heads,
you know, try to get as many resources for their department.
Is that the same way with the deans trying to?
I think so, but he wouldn't be able to do that without having the strong faculty and the strong programs of the faculty of Shellock to do that.
But you have to have both there, and I think it's due to both.
Plus, we've had a central administration
who has seen the value in having a strong college education.
Has that changed from administration to administration?
Oh, yeah.
Yeah.
A lot?
Just, I mean.
Where do we stand on these things?
I'll throw them out if you want me to.
Well, you're just going to have this stuff, right?
OK. We're probably in the most difficult period we've ever been in right now.
OK.
Simply perception.
Two problems.
A lack of knowledge of the role and scope of the College of Education.
Because of the number of, because of the complexity of the institution now.
Right.
A lack of interest, but a lack of... Embodyment?
Not being able to devote the amount of time necessary to get up to speed and to learn what needs to be learned.
Because there's so many other areas which the administration is familiar with, they're already comfortable in those settings, so it's much easier to go ahead in those settings.
To re-educate or re-educate?
Yeah, and we're talking ground zero.
So, it's... Yeah, that's a problem.
That's a problem.
But up until this time, we've had really good support.
I don't think we have it now.
But it takes a lot more effort on our part to communicate.
Let me address outside.
OK.
Inside the institution, we have gone from no
that there being very little of any perception that we even have a college of education.
Literally what many superintendents and principals and personnel directors say is that now the best college of education is here.
And in fact, I get calls all the time telling me or asking me, what can I do to recruit your kids?
I want her just like her.
or two more just like him.
He's coming from a wide variety all over the state.
Our kids are in really good demand.
Of course, a lot of it has to do with the caliber of kid that comes in at the beginning of the program.
We like to think it's all program A, but it's not.
It's a combination of the two.
Our graduate students have gotten placements.
Our undergraduate students get very good placements.
And I think the perception has been for the last few years and is that if you want this program at any stage, you go to Texas Freshman and transfer increase this year over last year was 54%.
As a whole, we had a 9% increase, but if you take the number of new freshman transfers,
One September 86 to one September 87 had a 54% increase.

One piece, if you're not familiar with this, that I think is important for you to build in at some point, Sylvia, and it's not related to exactly what you're asking me, but I can give you a chart which shows this.
For the past eight years or so, and I haven't gone back further than that, we get our students
particularly at the undergraduate level in the College of Education, was really interesting.
Because for about the last four years, we would start with a freshman class in about 250 to 275, which represented fairly consistently about 3% of the total university freshman class.
When that class became a sophomore, it had grown to over 400.
It represented roughly 6% of that class at the university.
When that class became a junior, it represented over 8% of that class at the university, a number somewhere 600 to 700 students.
When that class became a senior,
It represented anywhere from 10 to over 11 percent of the university senior class and numbered in the neighborhood of 9 to 9.50.
And one of the things that concerns me is that this year we had such a significant increase in our freshman class.
The university had such a significant increase in its freshman class.
So if I'm looking at a higher percentage right now as freshmen, what are we looking at?

And the trends will tell us that we'll be looking at 10% to 11% of that senior class four years down the road, which we'll have in the neighborhood, could have in the neighborhood of 11 to 1,200 seniors.
Well, how do you feel that all this upheaval and this change, this drastic
that we're looking at in the whole teacher education program is going to affect, because these will be under the old program anyway, right?
These that entered this year will be in the same one.
But what's going to happen now?
I mean, I know nobody knows for sure, but how do you feel about what might happen?
I'm torn between, one, wanting to control the numbers, to be compatible with resources so we have a quality program,

with the other side that i want to produce as many good teachers as we can because our kids are getting a good experience are being received well and are doing good jobs and i don't want to cut back for equality's sake supposedly and for some other reasons that might help us here we're returning kids away to other programs which they may or may not get as good preparation
plus I have some concern with the land grant mission.
On the other side, you can't prepare everybody.
Just like I was saying, I've got 163 kids right now, and I have noticed, I've commented several times on how I don't feel like I have done as good a job in the classroom this time as in the past.
And that has a lot to do with my style in terms of, because I like a lot of interaction.
I've been trying to know all my kids.
I wind up knowing none of my kids.
That kind of thing.
OK.
Some of the highlights, perhaps.
And you were here as a student.
You got your master's and your doctorate at Texas A&M.
And then you also started working here right after you graduated.
Well, you were working while you were getting the degrees.
So tell me how that changes.
Because I haven't even started doing anything with students yet.
But looking back now to your years as a student,
And then as it penetrated all the way to the top, how has that evolved in your own perceptions?
How do you see it now versus how you saw it when you were a student, maybe?
Yeah.
As a student, I tended to see things more simplistically, which in all bad.
Well, there probably were a lot simpler then, too, I mean.
Yeah.
A lot of the issues were a lot simpler.
I think that we had some really good faculty back then.
I felt very good about my experience both at the master's and the doctoral level.
Some of those same folks who were their strengths then are still, you know, strengths today.
Shoots, Steny Johnson.

Someone told me that 90%, and I was asked to verify this, and I don't know why I have to go through the document, that 90% of the people that Dean Hubert, attributing the fact that he was so astute in picking the right kinds of people for the life, that 90% of the people that he had hired were still here and were still productive.
Does that sound high?
It wouldn't be too high.
I mean, that's going to be pretty close.
And I can vouch for that.
Both he and Dean Corrigan
Now they see, he saw and Dean Corbin sees that the most important function that Dean plays is in the recruitment and hiring the very best faculty.
Without that, everything else just falls apart.
And so they both place heavy, heavy emphasis on that.
I know Dr. Hewlett many times.
And Corgan, too, just gnashed teeth over those decisions because they don't look at it just as hiring an individual, but rather as an investment in the state, in the lives of our young people.
Because if you take a person today making a $30,000 or $40,000 decision just to bring that person in,
you're making in excess of a million or two million dollar decision over the life of that professor.
So when you couch it in those kinds of terms, and particularly at the tenure point, that's really when you're really assessing the value of that individual to the program.
Is the hiring still done?
you know, on recommendations from the departments and the process.
I had one teacher say, you know, that if they were hired by Dean Huber, just outright said, if you will not accept that position, you just went to interview, you can have a job here.

And she says it was great, but in thinking back, she says that's not the way it should have been done because, you know, it should be done by the department and what are the needs, you know, that kind of thing.
Was that just something that happened once in a while or was it just a...

unusual yeah typically it he bobbed out of the park recommendation but his recommendation very strong and if that's usually in other words now what is the process when you're going to when you need a new position how does that evolve a new tenure track position okay the department heads
will consult with their faculty in terms of what that position is.
Or if we have a position where someone leaves, they may want to take that position and redefine it.
So it starts with the definition of the position in the department.
And then that definition is shared with the dean and massaged and looked at in light of its compatibility with him a little bit or what have you.
That's agreed upon.
And then the departments advertise that position nationally through the search process.
And it's a faculty search process.
And typically, then, we'll bring in three to four people.
And then out of that two or three day interview process, the one who stops on that will be the dean.
And then at the end of that process, the department head
or however the department is structured, will get input from all the different interview stops.
Because typically they involve faculty large group, faculty small group, program area, one-on-one, graduate students, dean, phillips, as in faculties typically.
And they will synthesize all that input and then make the determination.
And also, they generally have a seminar that they will give for faculty and graduate students.
Then the department head will bring the faculty's record.
